    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-08-31T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-08-31T11:00:00-05:00" n="562"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d562">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.9312 (Aggressor)/5: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-08-31T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 31, 1937—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 31—12:54 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>212. In calling formally today on Bismarck, acting chief of the Political Bureau
                    of the Foreign Office, he raised the question of Germany’s <pb facs="0507"
                        n="500" xml:id="pg_500"/> concern over her Far Eastern interests. He then
                    confidentially said, referring to the recent Sino–Russian Pact, that while it
                    was only natural that China in the position in which she finds herself would
                    wish to close her back door it nevertheless complicated Germany’s consideration
                    of the situation.</p>
                <p>(The press here asserts the existence of secret clauses.)</p>
                <p>I would say that the situation here is that while Germany is, of course,
                    carefully considering the political implications of the substance and possible
                    intent of this agreement a most important element in its effect on German policy
                    is the probable emotional reaction of Hitler.</p>
                <p>By mail to London, Paris, Moscow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
